	                              	<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#333333" style="font-size:12px;">
	                              		Recently, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), has hiked the Repo Rate and Reverse Repo by 25 basis points to 7.50% pa and 6.50% pa respectively while there has been no change to the CRR.
	                              	</font>
	                            	</p>
                                	<p align="justify">
                                		<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#333333" style="font-size:12px;">
                                			The hike comes close post the RBI’s annual monetary policy review on May 3, 2011, when it raised the Repo Rate by 50 basis points and the Reverse Repo Rate by 50 basis points to 7.25% pa and 6.25% pa respectively. (Repo Rate is the rate at which RBI provides liquidity to the commercial banks while Reverse Repo Rate is the rate earned by banks on the excess liquidity parked with RBI). The savings rate has been hiked from 3.5% pa to 4% pa while both the CRR and Bank Rate had been left unchanged at 6% during this review too.
                                		</font>
                                	</p>
                                	<p align="justify">
                                		<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#333333" style="font-size:12px;">
                                			As a result of the recent hikes in the rates by RBI, loans are set to become more expensive, with most banks preparing to increase their lending rates after the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) raised key policy rates for the 10th occasion in 15 months as illustrated in the table below - 
